ΙΙ. 6. 16. Subtristis visus est esse aliquantulum mihi. The propriety os behaviour necessary to the different characters of the son and the lover is wonderfully preserved in this instance. A deceit sustained with great assurance, would not have been agreeable to the character of an ingenuous youth: and it would have been improbable, in the character of the lover, to have entirely smothered his concern. He suppresses it, therefore, in some measure, because the thing was to be concealed; but could not assume a thorough joyfulness, because his disposition and passion inspired him with melancholy. So far Donatus.

It may be added also, as a further answer to Diderot‚ that the words with which Pamphilus concludes this act, alluding to his present situation, assign a very natural reason for his subduing the transports of his anger towards Davus. ·
